{"questionId":"11731","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>The curve&nbsp;<span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"y = f\\left( x \\right)\">\n  <mi>y</mi>\n  <mo>=</mo>\n  <mi>f</mi>\n  <mrow>\n    <mo>(</mo>\n    <mi>x</mi>\n    <mo>)</mo>\n  </mrow>\n</math></span>&nbsp;is shown in the graph, for&nbsp;<span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"0 \\leqslant x \\leqslant 10\">\n  <mn>0</mn>\n  <mo>⩽</mo>\n  <mi>x</mi>\n  <mo>⩽</mo>\n  <mn>10</mn>\n</math></span>.</p>\n<p><img style=\"display:block;margin-left:auto;margin-right:auto;\" src=\"__IMG__/0a44fa05389ed914ed86a1ea66c71882666a4a36.png\"></p>\n<p>The curve&nbsp;<span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"y = f\\left( x \\right)\">\n  <mi>y</mi>\n  <mo>=</mo>\n  <mi>f</mi>\n  <mrow>\n    <mo>(</mo>\n    <mi>x</mi>\n    <mo>)</mo>\n  </mrow>\n</math></span>&nbsp;passes through the following points.</p>\n<p><img style=\"display:block;margin-left:auto;margin-right:auto;\" src=\"__IMG__/adf9974b6e26c279a59fd52f8b99005acb9af1e3.png\"></p>\n<p>It is required to find the area bounded by the curve, the <span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"x\">\n  <mi>x</mi>\n</math></span><em>-</em>axis, the <span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"y\">\n  <mi>y</mi>\n</math></span><em>-</em>axis and the line <span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"x = 10\">\n  <mi>x</mi>\n  <mo>=</mo>\n  <mn>10</mn>\n</math></span>.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p>Use the trapezoidal rule to find an estimate for the area.</p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p>Area =&nbsp;<span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"\\frac{2}{2}\\left( {2 + 2\\left( {4.5 + 4.2 + 3.3 + 4.5} \\right) + 8} \\right)\">\n  <mfrac>\n    <mn>2</mn>\n    <mn>2</mn>\n  </mfrac>\n  <mrow>\n    <mo>(</mo>\n    <mrow>\n      <mn>2</mn>\n      <mo>+</mo>\n      <mn>2</mn>\n      <mrow>\n        <mo>(</mo>\n        <mrow>\n          <mn>4.5</mn>\n          <mo>+</mo>\n          <mn>4.2</mn>\n          <mo>+</mo>\n          <mn>3.3</mn>\n          <mo>+</mo>\n          <mn>4.5</mn>\n        </mrow>\n        <mo>)</mo>\n      </mrow>\n      <mo>+</mo>\n      <mn>8</mn>\n    </mrow>\n    <mo>)</mo>\n  </mrow>\n</math></span>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <em><strong>M1A1</strong></em></p>\n<p>Area = 43&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p><em><strong>[3 marks]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"11731","referenceCode":"EXM.2.AHL.TZ0.12a","subjectId":"51-dp-mathematics-applications-and-interpretation","title":"Use the trapezoidal rule to find an estimate for the area.","paper":"2","level":"HL","questionNumber":"a","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 3]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 4—Statistics and probability","Topic 5—Calculus","Topic 5—Calculus","SL 5.8—Trapezoid rule","Topic 4—Statistics and probability","AHL 4.13—Non-linear regression"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":2}